uminates the ways that we live with and without water, and explores how we can think and write with water on land. Water offers a way of attending to emerging and enduring social and ecological concerns and making sense of them in lively and creative ways. By approaching Living with water from different disciplinary and methodological perspectives, and drawing on research from around the world, this collection opens up discussions that reinvigorate and renew previously landlocked debates.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 6, Clean water and sanitation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHydrologyxSocial aspects. 0aWaterxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aClean water and sanitation.  aanthropocene.  abodies of water.  acities.  aecologies.  aethnography.  aeveryday life.  apoetics.  aswimming.  awater cultures.  awater histories.1 aBack, Les, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBates, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBates, Charlotte, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBates, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBinitie, Wayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaws, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlutter, Lorna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFredriksen, Aurora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarde-Hansen, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrzywonos, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Jessica J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re